54
00:03:07.480 --> 00:03:11.180
As we all know, there are three main types of

55
00:03:11.900 --> 00:03:15.720
radiation therapy. Of course, external beam radiation, IR.

56
00:03:17.440 --> 00:03:21.040
About 60% of patients get this through rad onc

57
00:03:21.060 --> 00:03:23.200
departments, external beam radiation.

58
00:03:23.580 --> 00:03:27.340
Also insertional brachytherapy, where isotopes inserted into pledgets

59
00:03:27.400 --> 00:03:30.620
and pills and little delivery

60
00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:35.560
vesicles, and those can be delivered specifically in a cancer, especially in head

61
00:03:35.570 --> 00:03:37.859
and neck and cervical cancer, these type of approaches.

62
00:03:38.220 --> 00:03:42.140
And of course, what we're talking about today is actually injectable radionuclide

63
00:03:42.160 --> 00:03:45.760
therapy. We want to emphasize that this is

64
00:03:45.880 --> 00:03:48.740
different. This is molecularly targeted

65
00:03:49.360 --> 00:03:50.140
radiation

66
00:03:51.580 --> 00:03:55.280
that is fundamentally different than the local radiation with intent for

67
00:03:55.400 --> 00:03:58.880
cure of traditional external beam radiation and insertional

68
00:03:58.900 --> 00:04:02.460
brachytherapy. And also to remind ourselves that it's fundamentally

69
00:04:02.480 --> 00:04:06.420
systemic because you've got the pharmacokinetics of a circulating

70
00:04:06.480 --> 00:04:09.620
affinity ligand of some sort or another with an isotope.

71
00:04:10.470 --> 00:04:14.340
And we are hypothesizing that that makes a difference in terms of the biological

72
00:04:14.440 --> 00:04:16.380
mechanisms, and so we'll explore some of that.

73
00:04:18.060 --> 00:04:21.721
Fundamentally, we think about radionuclide mechanism of action as starting with

74
00:04:22.260 --> 00:04:25.350
ROS and DNA damage in sort of the traditional sense,

75
00:04:25.840 --> 00:04:29.670
maybe traditionally single-strand DNA breaks with beta radiation,

76
00:04:30.300 --> 00:04:34.140
double strand with alpha radiation, and maybe very

77
00:04:34.200 --> 00:04:37.020
local double strand breaks with Auger electrons.

78
00:04:37.240 --> 00:04:40.800
I think clearly there's some mix of that as we study this a little bit more.

79
00:04:40.860 --> 00:04:44.780
And single-strand breaks can be converted to double-strand breaks, et cetera,

80
00:04:44.900 --> 00:04:48.700
through DNA damage response within cells, fundamentally leading to maybe

81
00:04:48.780 --> 00:04:52.450
apoptosis, necrosis, and ferroptosis, as well as immunogenic cell

82
00:04:52.580 --> 00:04:55.740
death. And we'd like to concentrate on that.

83
00:04:55.760 --> 00:04:59.590
What's the implications of that in terms of molecularly targeted

84
00:04:59.880 --> 00:05:03.670
radiation and explore that concept a little bit more

85
00:05:03.760 --> 00:05:07.540
deeply and mechanistically. Now, if we go back to external beam

86
00:05:07.600 --> 00:05:10.080
radiotherapy and tumor immune response,

87
00:05:11.180 --> 00:05:15.040
external beam is delivered locally with curative intent for

88
00:05:15.160 --> 00:05:15.660
cancer,

89
00:05:16.480 --> 00:05:20.140
but there's lots of activity going on outside the directed beam.

90
00:05:20.780 --> 00:05:23.860
So it's well documented that external beam

91
00:05:24.280 --> 00:05:28.040
radiation can be immune activating, traditional

92
00:05:28.600 --> 00:05:31.960
X-ray therapy. It reprograms the tumor microenvironment.

93
00:05:31.990 --> 00:05:35.600
There's been work looking at how it can induce immunogenic cell death and release

94
00:05:35.700 --> 00:05:37.200
DNA, RNA, and PAMPs,

95
00:05:38.240 --> 00:05:40.760
activates innate immunity, and may generate

96
00:05:41.120 --> 00:05:44.310
neoantigens for presentation to dendritic cells.

97
00:05:45.220 --> 00:05:45.720
Ultimately,

98
00:05:46.640 --> 00:05:49.450
there's evidence that it can engage the adaptive immunity.

99
00:05:50.480 --> 00:05:52.420
Often talked about as the abscopal effect,

100
00:05:53.740 --> 00:05:55.520
responses outside the radiation field.

101
00:05:55.540 --> 00:05:58.760
But when you talk to practitioners, that's actually pretty rare.

102
00:05:58.920 --> 00:06:02.636
Everybody's got an example of it, but it's actually pretty rare.It's

103
00:06:02.716 --> 00:06:06.416
also external beam radiation could be immune suppressive, and that's well

104
00:06:06.456 --> 00:06:10.196
documented. It can recruit Tregs, and

105
00:06:10.296 --> 00:06:12.916
MDSCs, and immunosuppressive

106
00:06:13.956 --> 00:06:16.676
macrophages, sort of quote "M2-type macrophages,"

107
00:06:18.256 --> 00:06:21.176
can actually induce increased expression of PD-L1 on tumor cells,

108
00:06:21.236 --> 00:06:24.976
and induces immune checkpoint signatures.

109
00:06:25.056 --> 00:06:26.736
So external beam

110
00:06:28.736 --> 00:06:32.716
in relation to systemic radioligand therapy, the question is,

111
00:06:32.796 --> 00:06:36.756
can radioligand therapy, because it's systemic, actually induce a more

112
00:06:36.876 --> 00:06:40.596
prominent immune activation? That's sort of the fundamental query

113
00:06:40.656 --> 00:06:44.496
of these investigations. So

114
00:06:44.536 --> 00:06:45.356
when we look at that,

115
00:06:46.476 --> 00:06:50.036
despite some beneficial immune activating effects, radioligand

116
00:06:50.056 --> 00:06:53.936
therapy, as people are starting to look at the mechanisms, can certainly have

117
00:06:53.976 --> 00:06:57.836
some suppressive effect. One of it is just simply the radiosensitivity of effector

118
00:06:57.916 --> 00:07:01.876
cells by any radiation, especially

119
00:07:02.696 --> 00:07:06.336
CD8 T cells and NK cells are highly radiosensitive, so we always have to

120
00:07:06.356 --> 00:07:09.876
consider that. Crossfire is actually one interesting

121
00:07:10.016 --> 00:07:13.896
aspect of especially beta radiation, but to some

122
00:07:13.916 --> 00:07:16.736
degree alpha, the field effects of the radiation.

123
00:07:17.276 --> 00:07:20.916
That could actually be an advantage with tumor heterogeneity.

124
00:07:20.926 --> 00:07:21.456
As we know,

125
00:07:22.976 --> 00:07:26.436
the heterogeneity of tumor antigens are well

126
00:07:26.516 --> 00:07:30.416
documented, and in precision medicine, you kind of have to target the cell,

127
00:07:30.456 --> 00:07:34.106
and one way to avoid that with traditional precision mechanism

128
00:07:34.596 --> 00:07:37.356
and small molecules is lack of antigen

129
00:07:37.396 --> 00:07:41.196
presentation. The field effect of radioisotopes, though,

130
00:07:41.276 --> 00:07:42.596
